            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1413929192,
            "creation_date": 1413928704,
            "body": "<p>Your itunes Class is extending <code>ConsoleProgram<\/code> as well. <\/p>\n\n<p>That means, the moment you create an instance of this class, a <em>second<\/em> console will be created, where the output of that class goes to. <\/p>\n\n<p>For this reason, you are seeing the output if you <code>return<\/code> the values (they are printed by the first <code>ConsoleProgram<\/code>, working with the first Console you are currently viewing.) <\/p>\n\n<p>You should either switch your console view (assuming eclipse) or don't create a second <code>ConsoleProgram<\/code> from within your main program. It seems like a regular class (without extending <code>ConsoleProgram<\/code>) would serve your needs. <\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Also if I wanted to return both the string name and int year from a\n  single function, \n      can I do that? In that case what will be the return type?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>There are various options:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>You could return a <code>List&lt;Object&gt;<\/code> with a specific position for each returned value.<\/li>\n<li>You could use private properties (and getters) in the <code>iTunes<\/code> class, ans access your result after processing the input (<code>itunes.getName(); itunes.getYear();<\/code>)<\/li>\n<li>You could create your own Result Object, containing all the required return parameters.<\/li>\n<li>and many more ...<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 26497092,
            "question_id": 26496892,
            "last_edit_date": 1413929192
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed783ecfe6b4babe78d4ae5b206ef431?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1690035,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1552587,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1552587/titus",
                "reputation": 22554,
                "display_name": "Titus",
                "accept_rate": 40
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1413928906,
            "creation_date": 1413928906,
            "body": "<p>The <code>println()<\/code> method of the <code>ConsoleProgram<\/code> class doesn't print the object to the standard output, it prints it to the <code>IOConsole<\/code> which is an <code>java.awt.Container<\/code> that has to be added to a <code>Frame<\/code> of <code>JFrame<\/code>. If you want to print those values to the console use <code>System.out.println(...)<\/code> instead.<\/p>\n\n<p>In answer to your second question. To return both an <code>int<\/code> and a <code>String<\/code> you can set that method's return type to <code>Object[]<\/code> but in this case you should create some Getters and Setters for the <code>itunes<\/code> class.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26497148,
            "question_id": 26496892
        }
    ],
